<center><table border=0><tr><td><center><H2><font face=arial>Re: Changes needed for PvP to work in Everquest</font></H2></center>
<font face=arial size=2><b>Posted By:</b> <A HREF="/cgi-local/whois2.cgi?dylan waite">dylan waite</a><br>
<b>Posted On:</b> 7:51 a.m. 12/2/1999<br>
<b>Subject:</b> Re: Changes needed for PvP to work in Everquest<p>
<br><center><img src="http://www.everworld.net/pvpquest/images/divider.gif" width=452 height=22 border=0></center><BR><P ALIGN=CENTER><b>In Reply To:</b> <A HREF="http://www.everworld.net/cgi-local/pvp.cgi?read=778" TARGET=_self>Changes needed for PvP to work in Everquest</A> (TheBlack[BCK])
</STRONG><FONT SIZE=2 color=#FFFFFF FACE=arial>
<P>> The following assumes that Verant is willing to make some PvP

<BR>&gt; specific changes to the code base in order to facilitate PvP
<BR>&gt; combat in Everquest. If that assumption is invalid, it is my
<BR>&gt; opinion that the current system will not prove viable.
<P>&gt; First the problems:
<P>&gt; #1 Level based PvE system is too restrictive in determining
<BR>&gt; attack, damage, and spell resistance for PvP combat.
<P>&gt; #2 It is too difficult if not impossible to kill another player
<BR>&gt; given the ease with which players can zone, camp and log out, or
<BR>&gt; use SotW type spells to escape.
<P>&gt; #3 Grouping problems arise in PvP situations that must be
<BR>&gt; remedied so group combat can go forward.
<P>&gt; Now some solutions:
<P>&gt; #1 Have the combat system determine whether a player is engaged
<BR>&gt; in a PvE combat or a PvP combat. If it is a PvP combat then use
<BR>&gt; a modified set of algorithms for determining Attack, Damage, and
<BR>&gt; Spell Resistance. These algorithms should allow players within
<BR>&gt; +/-4 levels to have a reasonable chance of hitting, damaging,
<BR>&gt; and effecting with spells their opponents.
<BR>&gt; Where the code currently checks for twinking and limits it for
<BR>&gt; PvE this should be reduced or eliminated in the PvP environment.
<BR>&gt; Examples of this are characters with the same Attack and AC
<BR>&gt; numbers who are a few levels apart having drastically different
<BR>&gt; chances of hitting and damaging one another. Also weapons that
<BR>&gt; do less than their rated damage solely based on the characters
<BR>&gt; level. Spell resistance is also heavily slanted towards
<BR>&gt; character level, and this impact needs to be lessened.
<P>this is VERY open to exploit.......in the beta there was a problem with people circumventing the PvP switch by gathering several monsters in a "train" behind them and then dumping that train onto another player......what if i show up to PvP you, and i have a small train in tow
<P>&gt; #2 Fatigue should play an even greater role in PvP combats. When
<BR>&gt; a player goes below 3 bubbles they should begin to move slower.
<BR>&gt; At 2 bubbles remaining add an additional slow down and begin
<BR>&gt; scaling that slow down in a linear fashion as 0 health is
<BR>&gt; approached. At 1 bubble all SotW type spells should be
<BR>&gt; ineffective or have a minimal effect. Add a "Sprint"
<BR>&gt; skill that when used causes SotW to be in effect for a short
<BR>&gt; duration (15 to 20 seconds) and uses fatigue. Fighters should
<BR>&gt; have a much greater Sprint proficiency than other classes
<BR>&gt; (especialy those that get SotW spells). The higher the
<BR>&gt; character's stamina the longer the Sprint should last and the
<BR>&gt; hit to stamina should be slightly lesssened, to make this
<BR>&gt; primarily a fighter skill.
<P>&gt; #3 For PvP characters to group, all characters in the party
<BR>&gt; should be within two levels of the highest level character plus
<BR>&gt; one level for every 10 levels the highest character has. A 15th
<BR>&gt; level top character could have in his group any characters 12th
<BR>&gt; level or higher. Such a group can attack any other group that
<BR>&gt; consists of at least 2/3 members within this range. I call this
<BR>&gt; the group attack rating (GAR). The 15th character has a GAR of
<BR>&gt; 12 to 18, so groups with 2/3 members in that range could be
<BR>&gt; attacked. Again take the highest level character and divide by
<BR>&gt; 10 then add 2 to get the offset +/- to his level.
<BR>&gt; When an individual or a group attacks another group, then a
<BR>&gt; group combat flag is set and everyone in the two groups is
<BR>&gt; tracked as being in combat with one another. Individuals that
<BR>&gt; meet the normal +/-4 level requirements can engage group
<BR>&gt; members, but by attacking a grouped player they are attacking
<BR>&gt; the entire group and can then be attacked by all members of that
<BR>&gt; group.
<BR>&gt; When a player forms a group they should have to give it a name
<BR>&gt; (this is part of the existing interface). It should be clear to
<BR>&gt; anyone attempting to attack a member of a group that they are
<BR>&gt; part of a group and which group they are part of.
<P>&gt; Finally add a /gduel function that allows one group to challenge
<BR>&gt; another outside of the normal GAR or individual level
<BR>&gt; restrictions. A /duel or /gduel challenge should only last for
<BR>&gt; 60 seconds after which time if not accepted it times out. Only
<BR>&gt; members in the group at the time the /gduel was issued will be
<BR>&gt; flagged as combatants to both groups when the duel is accepted.
<BR>&gt; Issuing a /gduel will also send the list of names of the
<BR>&gt; characters in the challenge group along with their levels (no
<BR>&gt; anonymous /gduel).
<P>&gt; If these three areas are addressed I feel that Everquest can
<BR>&gt; have a workable PvP system worthy of support by the PvP
<BR>&gt; community. None of these changes are designed to impact the PvE
<BR>&gt; environment or combat system in any way. They could and should
<BR>&gt; be implemented to the main code base as opposed to being added
<BR>&gt; for the PvP server alone.
<BR>
</FONT></td></tr></table></P>
